library(TeachingPopGen)

Background

Natural Selection is, of course, the basis for the Darwinian theory of evolution, and perhaps surprisingly, it is something we have barely touched upon up to this point. The reason for that is important - without first having a thorough understanding of the stochastic processes of drift, mutation and so forth, it is difficult if not impossible to infer the action of selection in any definitive way. So having done that, we now want to look at the genetics of selection; in so doing, we will follow address the following three questions:

  1. Taken by itself, how do we expect selection to affect allele and genotype frequency dynamics?
  2. At a theoretical level, how should selection, mutation and drift interact?
  3. Given that theoretical basis, how can we identify the effects of selection based on molecular sequence data?

Fitness

Fitness is, broadly speaking, the contribution made by an individual to the subsequent generation, as measured by numbers of viable and fertile progeny. For our purposes, of course, since we are interested in allele frequency dynamics in diploid population, what we really want to be considering is the contributions made by individuals of a given genotype. In doing so, there are a couple of considerations we need to take into account

Fitness components

Numerous factors contribute to fitness, among them

  1. Fertility. In order to contribute to subsequent generations, an individual has to be capable of producing viable gametes.
  2. Mating success. Having produced those gametes, s/he needs to mate successfully.
  3. Viability of progeny Having mated, the resulting embryos must survive to reproductive age
  4. Fertility of progeny And finally, those reproductive age progeny have to themselves be fertile

In fact, there are many more elements that can be examined; we are going to restrict most of our attention to viability as a measure of fitness, briefly considering fertility as somewhat of a special case.

Absolute vs. relative fitness

In our simple formulation, fitness is measured by the average number of progeny produced by individuals of a particular genotype. But, just as we did when we first developed Hardy-Weinberg theory, we need to be able to use those numbers to generate expectations about frequencies, both of genotypes and alleles.

Consider the following example. We are looking at a mouse coat color polymorphism, with two alleles, C and R:

fC <-.3
fR <-.7

Furthermore, based on experimental observation, we observe that the viabilities of the three genotypes are as follows:

wCC <-.5
wCR <- .4
wRR <- .3
w <-c(wCC,wCR,wRR)

Now, suppose we have a population of 100,000 newborn mice (before selection has occurred) and the population is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium. That would mean that we would have the following numbers of inviduals.

N <-100000
Ngenos.pre <-c(fC^2,2*fC*fR,fR^2)*N
Ngenos.pre
## [1]  9000 42000 49000

But, as they mature, the viability differences come into play, at reproductive age, the numbers become

Ngenos.post <-Ngenos.pre*w
N.post <- sum(Ngenos.post)
Ngenos.post
## [1]  4500 16800 14700
N.post
## [1] 36000

Note a couple of things here. First, whereas initially there were 100000 embryos, after selection, there are only 36000 adults. If we take the ratio of those two values, we get the mean fitness of the population

wbar <-N.post/N
wbar
## [1] 0.36

And note that the two factors that contribute to that are the genotype frequencies in the embryos (determined by the allele frequencies of the parents) and the viabilities of the those embryos as determined by their genotypes.

We can now ask the usual questions - is this new, post-selection, population of mice in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, and what are the allele frequencies? We will use our old hw function to do those calculations:

hw.post <-hw(Ngenos.post)
## [1] p= 0.358333333333333 q= 0.641666666666667
##        obs   exp
## [1,]  4500  4622
## [2,] 16800 16555
## [3,] 14700 14822
## [1] chi squared = 7.885 p =  0.005 with 1 d. f.
## [1] F =  -0.0148

And our answers are

  1. No, they are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, and
  2. The allele frequencies have changed. Whereas our starting frequency of the C allele was .3, we now see that it is .358.

But let’s look at another scenario. Suppose we repeat the above, only now assume that selection is 10 times more intense, that is that the viabilities of the three genotypes are .05, .04, and .03. We can repeat the same calculations as above:

w <-c(.05,.04,.03)
Ngenos.post <-Ngenos.pre*w
wbar <-sum(Ngenos.post/Ngenos.pre)
wbar
## [1] 0.12
Ngenos.post
## [1]  450 1680 1470
hw(Ngenos.post)
## [1] p= 0.358333333333333 q= 0.641666666666667
##       obs  exp
## [1,]  450  462
## [2,] 1680 1655
## [3,] 1470 1482
## [1] chi squared = 0.788 p =  0.375 with 1 d. f.
## [1] F =  -0.0148
## $Observed
## [1]  450 1680 1470
## 
## $Expected
## [1]  462.25 1655.50 1482.25
## 
## $Allele_freqs
## [1] 0.3583333 0.6416667
## 
## $Chisq
## [1] 0.7884539
## 
## $prob
## [1] 0.374568
## 
## $F
## [1] -0.01479915

And we see that the allele frequency change that results is identical to what we saw previously (although now there is not a significant difference from Hardy-Weinberg expecations in the genotype frequencies). This leads to an important point - It is the fitness of genotypes relative to those of others, that is important, as opposed to the absolute magnitudes of those fitnesses..

So from here on out, we will work with relative fitnesses, defined as follows. One genotype, usually that one with the highest absolute fitness, will be assigned a relative fitness of 1, and the others some values 1-s and 1-t, where s and t, the selection coefficients, reflect the intensity of selection and assume values between 0 and 1.

A Simple case - A Recessive Lethal

With a little simple algebra, we were able to show that, when an allele is a heterozygous lethal, its expected frequency at time t is simply

qt =[q/(1+q)]t

Where q is its initial frequency. we can see that graphically with the following code:

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
t <-c(0:100)
q <- .9
qt <-(q/(1+q))^t
plot(qt,type="l", xlab="Generation",ylab="q",ylim=c(0,1),col="red")

So what we see is that, as expected, the frequency of a recessive allele drops quickly, so that by 10 generations or so, it is effectively zero

A more general approach

We could repeat the algebra we did for lethal selection for other scenarios; for example where the fitness of the recessive homozygote is 1-s, where s<1. Instead of doing so, we can easily derive a more general equation, given the model of

w(AA) = 1
w(Aa) = 1-hs
w(aa) = 1-s

Having done so, we can then show that

δp = p(wA - w)/w

Where wA is the mean fitness of individuals with an A allele (homozygote or heterozygote) and w is the mean fitness of the population

The following R code implements that equation. It takes as inputs the initial value of p, the values of h and s, and whether or not a plot is to be returned. The default function returns a vector with the values of p.

deltap <-function(pinit,h,s,plot=FALSE){

p <-c(pinit,rep(0,99))
dpg <-c(0,rep(0,99))
for(i in 2:100){ 
pt <-p[i-1]
qt <-1-pt
wbar <-1-(2*pt*qt*h*s)-s*qt^2
dp<- ((pt*qt*s)*(pt*h+qt*(1-h)))/wbar
p[i] <-pt+dp

 }
p2 <- seq(0,1,.01); q2 <-1-p2
wbar2 <- 1-(2*p2*q2*h*s)-s*q2^2
dp2<- ((p2*q2*s)*(p2*h+q2*(1-h)))/wbar2
if(plot){
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
print(dp2)
plot(p, type="l", ylab="p", xlab="Generation", ylim=c(0,1),col="blue", main="Allele Frequencies vs. time")
lines(1-p,col="red")
plot(p2,dp2,type="l",xlab="p",ylab="Delta p", xlim =c(0,1), main="Delta(p) vs. p")
}
p

}

Selection against a deleterious recessive

We can start with the case of h=0 and s=1, the lethal situation we described above (we set the initial value of p to .1 and thus q to .9)

out <- deltap(.1,0,1)
plot(1-out,type="l",xlab="Generation",ylab="q",lwd=2,cex=1.5)
lines(1-deltap(.1,0,.2,plot=FALSE), col="blue",lwd=2,cex=1.5)
lines(1-deltap(.1,.5,.2),col="purple",lwd=2,cex=1.5)

Now, what is we had weaker recessive selection, say with s=.1?

lines(1-deltap(.1,0,.2,plot=FALSE), col="blue")

And we see that, as expected, while q declines, is does so much more slowly. But now let’s add in selection against the heterozygote as well, setting h to .5 (meaning that the fitness of the heterozygote is intermediate to that of the homozygote.

lines(1-deltap(.1,.5,.2),col="purple")

The differences, while present, are not spectacular. But what about rates of change? After all, that is what determines the rate of evolution. We can look at that with the same function, only now setting the plot flag to TRUE.

First, the lethal case:

x <-deltap(.1,0,1, plot=TRUE)

And we see that, as p increases, δp declines, meaning that when a detrimental allele becomes rare, selection becomes inefficient.

Now let us suppose that s=.1, as above

deltap(.1,0,.2,plot=TRUE)

How do we explain this? as p increases from zero, selection becomes more effective, as the number of AA and Aa genotypes(with a fitness of 1) increases, however, as aa individuals become rare, the efficiency declines.

Finally, if we set the fitness of the heterozygote to be intermediate to that of the two homozygotes:

deltap(.1,.5,.2,plot=TRUE)

Now we see that delta p is maximized when p=.5 . Of course, we know from Hardy-Weinberg theory that this is when heterozygotes are most common, and since selection in this case is acting on them, this result is as expected.

A special case - heterozygote advantage

All of the above have been examples of directional selection, with one allele or the other ultimately going to fixation. But what about the case of heterozygote advantage? For example, suppose that w have the following:

w(AA) = 1-s
w(Aa) = 1
w(aa) = 1-t

And as an example, suppose that s=.4 and t=.3. To use our function, we need to do some algebra to normalize relative fitnesses to that of AA, but when we do, we find that s=-.166 and h=-4, so we can plug those into our function and we get

deltap(.1,4,-.16,plot=TRUE)
abline(h=0,col="red")

There are two things to note. First of all, as expected, we see that there are nonzero equilibrium values for both p and q - after all, heterozygotes have the maximum fitness. This means that there are three equilibrium points in the δp vs. p curve, when p=0, p=1, or when p and q are at their equilibrium values.

But what is that mean fitness? We can calculate it as follows:

p <-(.3/(.4+.3))
q <-1-p
wbar <-1 - .4*p^2- .3*q^2
wbar
## [1] 0.8285714

And we see that it the mean fitness of the population is less than 1. Thus, the good news about heterozygote superiority is that it maintains variation. The bad news? At a cost to population fitness. We will address that more in the future.

Calculation of fitness from real data

To quickly summarize, we have been focusing on one component of fitness (viability) and modeling the impact of various models on allele frequency dynamics. In so doing, we have defined relative fitness, mean fitness, and selection coefficients and shown that, by itself, only heterozygote advantage leads to a stable polymorphism (at a cost in mean fitness). However, other than the hypothetical example we started our discussion with, we have not addressed how we might estimate fitness parameters from real data. In fact, this is something that is often difficult to do, especially when selection coefficients are small. However, it is not impossible.

This example involves the “tired old Bucephalus” of sickle cell anemia and goes from observed genotypes in a large sample of adults to an estimate of relative fitnesses of the three genomes. The approach is based on observed departure from Hardy Weinberg in those adults and the assumption that that deviation is the result of viability differences among the three genotypes.

Hardy-Weinberg Calculations

To start with, we can calculate the allele frequencies from the observed adult population and use them to determine the expected genotype distribution:

genos.n <-c(25374,5482,67)
genos.f <-round(genos.n/sum(genos.n),3)
p <-genos.f[1]+.5*genos.f[2]
genos.exp <-round(c(p^2,2*p*(1-p),(1-p)^2),3)
genos <-rbind(genos.f,genos.exp)
rownames(genos) <- c("Observed","Expected")
round(genos,30)
##           [,1]  [,2]  [,3]
## Observed 0.821 0.177 0.002
## Expected 0.827 0.165 0.008

We can then ask if the differences between observed and expected are significant:

hw(genos.n)
## [1] p= 0.909193803964687 q= 0.0908061960353135
##        obs   exp
## [1,] 25374 25562
## [2,]  5482  5106
## [3,]    67   255
## [1] chi squared = 167.655 p =  0 with 1 d. f.
## [1] F =  -0.0736
## $Observed
## [1] 25374  5482    67
## 
## $Expected
## [1] 25561.9838  5106.0324   254.9838
## 
## $Allele_freqs
## [1] 0.9091938 0.0908062
## 
## $Chisq
## [1] 167.6545
## 
## $prob
## [1] 0
## 
## $F
## [1] -0.07363204

And we see that in fact the chi-squared value is astronomical. So let’s proceed

Make some assumptions

In what follows, we make two assumptions:

  1. Mating is random, so at the time of zygote formation, HWE exists.
  2. Any observed departure from Hardy-Weinberg ratios in adults is due to egg-to-adult viability differences among genotypes

Calculate relative fitnesses

Given those assumptions there are two ways to proceed. First, we could assume that there was a pool embryos of some arbitrary size (larger than the number surveyed) in HW equilibrium, calculate the numbers of the genotypes in that pool and then calculate the ratio of observed individuals to those numbers:

embryos.n <-genos.exp*40000
w <-round(genos.n/embryos.n,3)
w
## [1] 0.767 0.831 0.209

And in keeping with our norm, we can calculate the values relative to the most fit genotype (which happens to be the heterozygote)

w <- round(w/max(w),3)
w
## [1] 0.923 1.000 0.252

But there is actually an easier way to get the same answer. We have observed frequencies, we also have expected ones, so let’s just take the ratio of those two:

w2 <-genos.f/genos.exp
w2 <-w2/max(w2)
round(w2,3)
## [1] 0.925 1.000 0.233

And we get essentially the same answer.

Summary

This is a classic textbook type of calculation. However, in addition to the assumptions we’ve already described, notice the magintude of the selecton coefficients:

s <- 1-w[1]
t <-1-w[3]
s;t
## [1] 0.077
## [1] 0.748

Both of these are very large. And remember, the calculation is based on observed departure from HW. In cases where selection coefficients are smaller (as is typical in most cases of polymorphisms), the departure from HW in a reasonable sample size is likely to be insignificant, rendering this sort of calculation suspect at best.

Adding in mutation

In our discussion thus far, we have used selection as the only factor affecting allele frequencies. Of course, in an ideal population, we also have to consider mutation. First, let’s consider a recessive detrimental allele. The loss due to selection will be q2 * w(AA), or q2 * (1-s). Since q2 ≈ 0, we can approximate this as -sq2. If the gain due to selection is μ , then equilibrium will be reached when

μ = sq2

or

q <- √ (μ/s)

As an example, we can look at some reasonable numbers - µ=10-7, s=.01

u <-10^-7
s <-.01
q1 <-sqrt(u/s)
q1
## [1] 0.003162278

So at equilibrium, we would expect an allele frequency of 0.0031623, which is small but not insignificant. We can also look at a range of values of s:

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
s <-seq(.002,.1,.001)
q <-sqrt(u/s)
plot(s,q,typ="l")

But now let’s assume that selection also acts against the heterozygote. We can proceed as follows:

  1. If q is small, then we can treat the number of aa homozgyotes as zero
  2. And in that case, p is nearly 1, so we can approximate the frequency of heterozygotes as 2q.

Thus, the reduction in the number of heterozygotes, using our previously established notation, will be 2qsh; with respect to little a alleles (half of those in the heterozygotes) it will be qsh. And, of course, once again, the gain due to mutation will be μ thus at equilibrium

µ = hsq

and

q = µ/hs

So let’s see what we get, keeping s at .01 but now adding in a weak effect (h=.1) on the heterozygote:

h=.1
s <-.01
q2 <-(u/(h*s))
q2
## [1] 1e-04

And comparing that with what we got above for the purely recessive case:

q2/q1
## [1] 0.03162278

So with an effect on heterozygote, equilibrium frequency of p much much lower (ca. two orders of magnitude). And we can look at that ratio (holding h and µ constant) over a range of values of s, yielding the following

s <-seq(.002,.1,.001)
q1 <-sqrt(u/s)
q2 <-u/(h*s)
plot(s,q2/q1,type="l",xlab="s",ylab="ratio")

And this makes a biologically important point. The equilibrium frequency of a detrimental allele is much lower when selection acts even weakly on the heterozygote as well as the homozygote.

Selection in finite populations

Now we need to address the joint effects of seletion and drift. Based on intuition, we would expect the following.

  1. Large population - drift is small; selection predominates
  2. Small population - drift stronger; case less clear

And before doing so, let’s go back about 40 years, to when it first became clear that polymorphism and heterozygosity are common features in populations of most species. Since simple selection theory, as we’ve covered thus far, predicts fixation or loss of alleles in most cases, this posed a problem, and indeed led to one of the great controversies in the history of evolutionary biology, the so called “selectionist-neutralist” debate. While the “debate” has long since lapsed, it is worthwhile to recall the neutralist argument, as it provides a null hypothesis for most experimental tests of natural selection hypotheses. The major tenets of the theory, as promulgated by Motoo Kimura and others, were simple:

  1. Populations are finite
  2. A large fraction of nucleotide or amino acid substitutions have no effect on fitness.
  3. Therefore, the stochastic processes of mutation and drift are responsible for most observed molecular variation.

So, under this model, levels of polymorphism and heterozygosity are determined largely by θ, which is of course 4Neµ. Indeed Kimura, in his 1971 paper (considered a classic) used this theory to estimate the effective population size of humans, using an estimate of µ of 10-7 /year, a generation time of 20 years, and average heterozygosity of .1:

Ne=function(H,u){
F <- 1-H
num <- (1/F)-1
denom <-4*u
Ne <-num/denom
Ne
}

as.integer(Ne(.1,10^-7*20))
## [1] 13888

Obviously, there are many assumptions made that add lots of uncertainty to this estimate; we needn’t belabor that point. But there was another problem. Remember that the “find-em and grind-em” era of electrophoresis was in full swing, so lots of data were being accumulated for lots of species. And here is the pattern that emerged.

taxa <-c("Dicots","Molluscs","Crustaceans","Insects","Drosophila","Fish","Amphibians", "Reptiles", "Birds", "Mammals")
H <-c(.05,.145,.08,.09,.12,.05,.07,.055,.05,.04)
Ntax <-sapply(H,Ne,u=10^-7)
barplot(Ntax/10000,names.arg=taxa,las=2,ylab=expression("Ne X 10"^-4))

So is it believable that as wide a variety of taxa would all have effective population sizes in a range of ∼10,000-40,000? Selectionists argued that this was a serious flaw in the neutral theory - mutation and drift simply could not explain the relative uniformity of heterozygosity levels observed in populations of such disparate organisms.

Drift and the strength of selection

For our discussion below, we are going to assume the following relative fitnesses (a simple additive model):

w(11) = 1
w(12) = 1+s
w(22) = 1+2s

Now, remember back to our discussion of the fate of a new mutation. At that time, we saw that, even with a selective advantage, in a finite population, the probability of loss, due simply to the sampling variance inherent in a Wright-Fisher population,is high. Following along with that logic, it is possible to show that the probability of survival of a new mutation in the first generation is approximately 2s/(1+s)2 . And as s gets small, 1+s approaches 1, so we can approximate this probability as simply 2s. For example:

s <-c(0,.01,.02,.05,.1,.2,.5,1)
p1 <-(2*s)/(1+s)^2
p2 <- 2*s
round(cbind(s,p1,p2),4)
##         s     p1   p2
## [1,] 0.00 0.0000 0.00
## [2,] 0.01 0.0196 0.02
## [3,] 0.02 0.0384 0.04
## [4,] 0.05 0.0907 0.10
## [5,] 0.10 0.1653 0.20
## [6,] 0.20 0.2778 0.40
## [7,] 0.50 0.4444 1.00
## [8,] 1.00 0.5000 2.00

But let’s take this one step further. Suppose it does survive and increase in frequency as a result of selection. How many alleles would we expect to observe in an infinite population? This is simply (1+s)t, however this is average of distribution including both those populations that have retained it as well as lost it. So consider with s=.01 and 1000 generations

pret=p1[2] # probability of survival in first generation 
mean.alleles <-(1+.01)^1000 # given survival, number of alleles after 1000 generations
mean.alleles
## [1] 20959.16

BUT - what is probability that a given population has lost the allele in the first generation?

1-pret
## [1] 0.9803941

So our distribution consists of 98% zeros. If we exclude them, then the average number of alleles is

mean.alleles/pret
## [1] 1069022

But this assumes N is infinite, which of course it is not. In the context of a finite Ne, what we want to do is to determine the probability of fixation. For a neutral allele, that probability is 4N, but what about when we add in s? The math is far from trivial (see Felsenstein pp. 253-258 for details), but the key result is in the following equation, which gives the probability of fixation of an allele with a positive selection coefficient of s and a population size of N:

NSeq8.1

Note that, as in the case of drift, in which the key parameter was 4Neµ, in this case it is 4Nes. But we can refine this a little bit more and ask how this probability varies with respect to p. That turns out to be a simple matter of adding 2p to the exponent in the numerator. We can explore that function graphically with the following functions:

fix.p <-function(Ns,cl="black"){
p <-seq(0,1,.01)

U <-(1-exp(-4*Ns*p))/(1-exp(-4*Ns))
lines(p,U,col=cl)
}
blank <- function() plot(0,bty='n',pch='',xlab='p',ylab='U', xlim =c(0,1),ylim=c(0,1))

First, let’s look at the case we did above, in which s=.01 and N varies between 10 and 10,0000

blank()
N <-c(10,25,50,100,200,500,1000,10000)
s=.01
Ns <-N*s
x <-sapply(Ns,fix.p)

Ns
## [1]   0.10   0.25   0.50   1.00   2.00   5.00  10.00 100.00

And we see that as Ns gets large, the probability of fixation of rare allele gets high (and in fact fixation becomes allele frequency-independent). But note also, these are for positive values of s (i. e. allele makes positive fitness contribution). What if selection is negative (s<0 in this notation)?

blank()
x <-sapply(Ns,fix.p)
Ns <--Ns
x <-sapply(Ns,fix.p, cl="red")

And prehaps not surprisingly, we get a mirror imaage of what we saw for positive selection.

But let’s set aside those cases where Ns is large and, regardless of p, probability of fixation or loss is essentially zero. To do so, we can focus on -.5<Ns<.5

blank()
Ns2 <-c(-.5,-.25,-.125,-.1,.1,.125,.25,.5)
x <-sapply(Ns2,fix.p)

The key point here is that selection doesn’t matter much - over this range of values, the probability of fixation doesn’t vary much from neutral expectations (Ns=0)

Tomoko Ohta (1976) investigated this further by looking at both probability of fixation and, perhaps more importantly, expected heterozygosity, for this case. In essence, the question she addressed was what are the predicted dynamics of weakly deleterious alleles in finite populations?

First, let’s look at fixation probability over the same range as above (-.5 < Ns <.5); furthermore we’ll assume that N=500, so 2N=1000, and we are varying s to vary Ns.

Ns2 <-c(seq(-1,-.01,.01),seq(.01,1,.01))

U2 <-(1-exp(-4*Ns2*.001))/(1-exp(-4*Ns2))
plot(4*Ns2,U2,type="l", xlab="4Nes",ylab="Fixation Probability",main="Fixation")

And no big deal here - when selected against, fixation probability is lowered; when positive it is raised.

But remember - our problem is to explain observed levels of heterozygosity. Again, we won’t grind through the math, but we can calculate the ratio of Het(Ns)/Het(neutral) at equilibrium by

het <-(2*(4*Ns2-1+exp(-4*Ns2)))/(4*Ns2*(1-exp(-4*Ns2)))

plot(4*Ns2,het,type="l",ylim=c(0,3),ylab="Relative Heterozygosity", xlab="4Nes",main="Heterozygosity")
abline(h=1,col="blue")

And to contrast them, let’s put them both on the same plot.

plot.new()
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
U2.norm <-U2/.001
plot(4*Ns2,U2.norm,type="l",col="red", main="Fixation Probability and Heterozygosity",xlab="4Ns",ylab="Relative to Neutral")
lines(4*Ns2,het,col="blue")
abline(v=0)
abline(h=1)

This figure is worth some careful consideration with respect to what it predicts about weakly selected alleles:

1.If selection is positive, then substitution rate increases much more quickly than does heterozygosity. This makes sense, since the stronger positive selection is, the more likely the favored allele will go to p=1 (and heterozygosity = zero). 2. The more interesting result is in the case of negative selection. Here we see the oposite kind of relationship - even when the probability of fixation is nearly zero, heterozygosity is comparable to that seen in a purely neutral case.

From these results, therefore, Ohta proposed that heterozygosity of weakly detrimental alleles would be expected to fall in a narrow range. The upper limit, of course, is determined by selection - if heterozygosity is high, the allele frequency must be high and thus there are more individuals (especially homozygotes) are the targets of selection. When heteozygosity is low, on the other hand, selection is inefficient, so that heterozygosity is a function of drift (which is, of course, mediated by population size).

Conclusions

So where are we at right now? Keep the following points in mind as we go forward:

  1. In basic selection models, only balancing selection results in stable polymorphisms, and it does so at a cost.
  2. Despite this, observed levels of polymorphism in populations are typically quite high.
  3. While strong selection can be inferred based on departures from Hardy-Weinberg, selection coefficients for most polymorphisms are likely quite small.
  4. If selection coefficients are small, then the joint effects of selection and drift, in theory, place upper and lower bounds on levels of heterozygosity in populations.

All of these, taken together, suggest that inference of the role of selection in shaping patterns of genetic variation in populations is an exceedingly difficult problem. In fact, what we have developed so far is really insufficient to do so. But what we haven’t taken into account is all of what molecular biology tells us. In particular, we have been treating all nucleotide substitutions equally. It’s time we develop a more nuanced view of genes and their structure.
